Ranunculus but still make it wintry.

These deep purple and ivory colors are perfect for this time of year, so I couldn't help but make a favorite version of ranunculus. Also fun to play with the stem color...adding a bit of green, brown, and plum to it make this usual spring bloom easier to use in a winter cake design. More fun to share soon!

Happy Valentine's Day!

I had a few little sugar roses leftover from class and decided to try them on a few cookies. While I know gumpaste would not be the tastiest part of the cookie, the roses look cute and would be great made in modeling chocolate (I couldn't get my hands on any in time)!

Wishing you a sweet and love-filled day!

NEW Live Tutorial!
Just in time for Spring...make a wafer paper ranunculus with me!

Join me in April for a 3-part lesson in making a wafer paper ranunculus from start to finish, including coloring, shaping and assembling petals, and finishing with a pretty calyx and clean flower stem.

All my tips and tricks plus TWO BONUS LESSONS on coloring my picotee ranunculus petals (two colorways), and tips for recreating other ranunculus flowers that inspire you.

ALL lessons will be recorded and saved in a private Facebook group so you can attend live, or watch whenever it's convenient for you. 

Tutorial is on SALE today through Monday!
I hope to see you!

My Wafer Paper Ranunculus livestream tutorial begins this Saturday April 22!

Join me for 3 lessons and learn how to make a full ranunculus flower in wafer paper, from the center to the finish of the calyx and stem. Plus, a BONUS lesson covering additional petal colorways and tips for recreating other ranunculus flowers you may find as inspiration.

Don't worry if you can't attend live, all the lessons will be recorded and saved in the private Facebook group where you can watch them at your convenience. Plus I'm there to answer questions and help you as needed!

Using a simple blossom cutter to make a daisy calyx.

Use what you have! 

Lengthen sections with a ball tool, then cut down the middle with scissors. Thin ends with dresden tool, then curl to add movement. Attach to the base of your daisy with sugar glue and dust to finish. I used Crystal Colors in Kiwi here.
